Exercise
Using a vector of integers, write a loop that prints:

‚ÄúFizz‚Äù if divisible by 3
‚ÄúBuzz‚Äù if divisible by 5
‚ÄúFizzBuzz‚Äù if divisible by both
The number otherwise

Use this vector: vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 15]

Solution


View solution

fn main() {
    let nums = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 15];

    for n in nums {
        if n % 15 == 0 {
            println!("FizzBuzz");
        } else if n % 3 == 0 {
            println!("Fizz");
        } else if n % 5 == 0 {
            println!("Buzz");
        } else {
            println!("{}", n);
        }
    }
}

Scope

Values outside of the for loop are accessible inside of it.
Values created inside of the for loop cannot be accessed outside of it.

Example: outer value used inside loop
fn main() {
    let greeting = "Hi";
    let names = vec!["Alice", "Bob"];

    for name in names {
        println!("{} {}!", greeting, name);
    }
}
Example: inner value not usable outside loop

This does not compile!

fn main() {
    let numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];

    for n in numbers {
        let doubled = n * 2;
        println!("{} doubled is {}", n, doubled);
    }

    // println!("Last doubled: {}", doubled); // ‚ùå `doubled` doesn't exist here
}

Create a vector of 5 or more f64 values (Vec&lt;f64&gt;)
Use a for loop to calculate the mean of the vector
Print the result







Note



We‚Äôve been working only with integers. To create a float (number with decimals) use 0.0 or specify the type manually e.g.¬†0f64.



Solution


View solution

fn main() {
    let x = vec![1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0];

    let n = x.len() as f64;
    let mut total = 0.0;

    for xi in x {
        total += xi;
    }

    println!("The mean is: {}", total / n);
}

Exercise

Create an empty vector
Append the values 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 using .push()
Clear the vector to make it empty
Lastly, extend it with another vector e.g.¬†[4.0, 5.0]
Print the final result.


Solution


View solution

fn main() {
    let mut x = Vec::new();
    x.push(1.0);
    x.push(2.0);
    x.push(3.0);
    x.clear();
    x.extend(vec![4.0, 5.0]);
    println!("{:?}", x);
}

